Title: The Last Shift
Credit: written by
Author: Filmwright example
Draft date: 2026-05-26
Notes: Scene 4 — the pivotal recognition. Plot loose, emotion heavy. POV: Meiling.

====

INT. CONVENIENCE STORE - NIGHT

Fluorescent hum. Rain sheets the glass. MEILING (50s, store apron over a winter coat, hands chapped raw) wipes a counter that is already clean.

On the sill by the door sits a paper bowl, steam thinning. The door is propped half-open. It always is.

The new sign outside catches the light: 旺铺转让.

A shape fills the doorway. KAI (70s, a coat too thin for the season, a plastic bag of cans) does not step in. He is looking at the sign.

MEILING
(not turning)
关东煮在窗边。拿了走吧。

He doesn't take it. He keeps reading the sign, slowly, the way a person reads something they already understood.

KAI
要关了。

MEILING
下周。

She rinses the cloth. Wrings it. The radio plays something far away.

KAI
你妈……

The cloth stops.

MEILING
她去年走的。

A long beat. The kettle ticks as it cools.

KAI
美玲。

The name lands. She does not turn around. Her thumb stops on the edge of the counter and stays there.

Outside, the rain. Inside, the hum. Neither of them moves.

MEILING (O.S.)
(barely)
......

She sets the cloth down. Carefully. Like it might break.

L-CUT TO:
